SIMPLE: penance
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Penance
<hw>Pen"ance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>penance</ets>, <ets>peneance</ets>, L. <ets>paenitentia</ets>
repentance. See <er>Penitence</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Repentance.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Wyclif (Luke xv.
7).</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Pain; sorrow; suffering.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧Joy or <xex>penance</xex> he feeleth none.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>A means of repairing a sin
committed, and obtaining pardon for it, consisting partly in the
performance of expiatory rites, partly in voluntary submission to a
punishment corresponding to the transgression, imposed by a confessor or
other ecclesiastical authority. Penance is the fourth of seven
sacraments in the Roman Catholic Church.</def> <rj><au>Schaff-Herzog
Encyc.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And bitter <qex>penance</qex>, with an iron whip.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Quoth he, ⟦ldquo⟧The man hath <qex>penance</qex> done,⟦br⟧
And <qex>penance</qex> more will do.⟦rdquo⟧</q>
<rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>Any act performed by a
person to atone for an offense to another; an act of atonement.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark> ⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Penance</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Penance
<hw>Pen"ance</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Penanced</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To impose penance;
to punish.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Some <xex>penanced</xex> lady elf.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Keats.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Penanceless</ent>⟦br⟧
